Hi %FIRSTNAME%,


The treatment for systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is evolving. As it evolves, it’s important to understand the safety and efficacy of SAPHNELO® (anifrolumab-fnia). This is why I want to share my perspective on choosing SAPHNELO as an add-on treatment option. 


SAPHNELO is indicated for the treatment of adult patients with moderate to severe SLE, who are receiving standard therapy. 


Limitations of Use: The efficacy of SAPHNELO has not been evaluated in patients with severe active lupus nephritis or severe active central nervous system lupus. Use is not recommended in these situations. 


This message is intended for US Healthcare Professionals. 


The recommended dosage of SAPHNELO is 300 mg, administered as an IV infusion over a 30-minute period, every 4 weeks.1


In terms of the impact on SLE disease activity across the affected organ systems, in the TULIP-2 study, the BICLA responder rate—the primary endpoint—was significantly higher with SAPHNELO 300 mg + ST at 47.8% (n=86/180) compared to 31.5% (n=57/182) for ST alone at Week 52 (P=0.001).1,2*†‡ This resulted in 53% more patients on SAPHNELO + ST who experienced disease activity reductions vs treatment with ST alone.


In the TULIP-1 study, the primary endpoint (SRI-4 responder rate) did not result in statistical significance; the secondary endpoint (BICLA) achieved improvement (descriptive only).1,3


It’s important to note that reduction in disease activity seen in BICLA and SRI-4 was related primarily to improvement in mucocutaneous and musculoskeletal organ systems.1


IMPORTANT SAFETY INFORMATION 

CONTRAINDICATION 

Known history of anaphylaxis with SAPHNELO. 


WARNINGS AND PRECAUTIONS 

  • Serious Infections: Serious and sometimes fatal infections have occurred in patients receiving immunosuppressive agents, including SAPHNELO. SAPHNELO increases the risk of respiratory infections and herpes zoster. Use caution in patients with severe or chronic infections. Avoid initiating treatment during an active infection and consider interrupting therapy in patients who develop a new infection during treatment (READ BELOW) 


Please see additional Important Safety Information below and full Prescribing Information, including Patient Information. 


I also want to call out key secondary endpoints (steroid-sparing and flare data).  


The TULIP-2 study demonstrated statistically significant steroid-sparing efficacy. In patients with a baseline OCS ≥10 mg/day, 52% of patients on SAPHNELO + ST (n=45/87) achieved and maintained OCS reduction to ≤7.5 mg/day vs 30% of patients on ST alone (n=25/83; P=0.004).1,2§|| Overall, this resulted in 72% more patients on SAPHNELO who achieved a sustained OCS dose reduction to ≤7.5 mg/day vs ST alone. Consistent trends were observed in MUSE and TULIP-1 trials, but the results were descriptive only.1


The TULIP-2 study also demonstrated a reduced annual flare rate, with more patients on SAPHNELO experiencing zero flares vs patients on ST alone.2,4,5¶ The annualized flare rate for patients on SAPHNELO + ST was 0.43 (N=180) compared with 0.64 for patients on ST alone (N=182); RR: 0.67 (95% CI: 0.48 to 0.94).2 Results did not reach statistical significance.


A post hoc subgroup analysis from TULIP-2 showed that 78% (n=35/45) of patients on SAPHNELO who had reduced OCS dose had no flares compared with 48% (n=12/25) of patients on ST alone. Note that the analysis for this post hoc data is descriptive only.4,5


In TULIP-1, the annualized flare rate was 0.60 for SAPHNELO + ST (N=180) compared with 0.72 for ST alone (N=184); difference: 0.83 (95% CI: 0.60 to 1.14).3 Results are descriptive only. 


Learn more about the safety and efficacy of SAPHNELO. 


Sincerely, 

Brittany Panico, DO, FACR 

Chief of Rheumatology at Summit Rheumatology 


*BICLA is a composite score of SLE disease activity that requires at least one level of improvement in all moderately or severely affected organ systems (reduction of all baseline BILAG A [severe] to B/C/D and baseline BILAG B [moderate] to C/D); no new organ involvement (≥1 new BILAG A or ≥2 new BILAG B); no worsening of disease activity as measured by SLEDAI-2K (worsening defined as an increase from baseline of >0 points) and PGA (worsening defined as an increase ≥0.30 points from baseline); no discontinuation of treatment; and no use of restricted medications.2,6

Learn about LYNPARZA® (olaparib) uses for high-risk early breast cancer


The overall survival results from the OlympiA clinical trial may be of interest to you. OlympiA was a phase 3, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, international study that evaluated LYNPARZA in patients with gBRCAm,* HER2-negative, high-risk† early breast cancer who had completed definitive local treatment and neoadjuvant or adjuvant chemotherapy. The primary endpoint was invasive disease-free survival (IDFS) and the secondary endpoint was overall survival (OS).


Please see Select Safety Information and disclaimers regarding the publication below.


*Select patients for this indication based on an FDA-approved companion diagnostic for LYNPARZA.1 †For patients who received prior neoadjuvant chemotherapy, high risk was defined as non-pCR in TNBC and as non-pCR with CPS&EG score ≥3 in HR-positive, HER2-negative disease. For patients who received prior adjuvant chemotherapy, high risk was defined as ≥pN1 or pN0 with ≥pT2 in TNBC and as ≥4 positive lymph nodes in HR-positive, HER2-negative disease.1


CPS&EG=pre-treatment clinical and post-treatment pathologic stage (CPS), estrogen receptor (ER) status, and histologic grade; gBRCAm=germline BRCA-mutated or germline BRCA mutation(s); HER2=human epidermal growth factor receptor 2; HR=hormone receptor; pCR=pathologic complete response; TNBC=triple-negative breast cancer.


Access the full publication to learn more about adjuvant LYNPARZA and review overall survival results in eligible patients with gBRCAm, HER2-negative early breast cancer.

CONTENT:

Every day I see new headlines about the effect that COVID-19 has had on the industry. It’s put us all in a state of uncertainty about the job market and industry prospects. But this isn’t the first time we’ve faced this kind of situation.


Back in 2008, it was a similar situation when the recession happened. Nobody knew what the future was going to be like, but if you look back, you’ll know that the industry bounced back. That’s because we focused on technologies of the future to make better decisions.
